                    "company": "INSERM",
                    "description": "Principal investigation: Development of anti-CD38 Affitins for Positron Emission Tomography (PET) imaging of multiple myeloma. \nAffitins are artificial affinity proteins with low molecular weight that exhibit comparable affinity and specificity to those of antibodies while being highly stable. They are generated by a fully in vitro process named ribosome display which allows the selection of proteins that can bind to a desired ligand. These different characteristics make Affitins excellent candidates for a use in imaging as an alternative to antibodies. We genetically engineered and characterized Affitins specific for CD38 protein, a marker for multiple myeloma cells. This work is still ongoing and will be followed by the preclinical evaluation of anti-CD38 Affitins. An imaging study based on the use of an anti-CD38 antibody radiolabelled with copper 64 has also been conducted in a murine model of myeloma. The objective was to shed a first light on CD38 targeting for imaging.",
